abstract: Article on stunned reaction by some parishioners to call by Bishop Orris Walker Jr, leader of Episcopal Diocese of Long Island, for resignation of Dean James Cardone, pastor of Cathedral of the Incarnation in Garden City, NY; Walker, citing worsening relations with Cardone, says his decision is final; Cardone, who is white, says Walker has unfairly accused him of racism and that Walker should have been removed from church years ago; photos (M)
snippet: Article on stunned reaction by some parishioners to call by Bishop Orris Walker Jr, leader of Episcopal Diocese of Long Island, for resignation of Dean James Cardone, pastor of Cathedral of the Incarnation in Garden City, NY; Walker, citing worsen...
lead_paragraph: WHEN Bishop Orris G. Walker Jr., leader of the Episcopal Diocese of Long Island, announced this month that he had asked for the resignation of Dean James J. Cardone, the pastor of the Cathedral of the Incarnation in Garden City, many parishioners were stunned by what seemed an abrupt and badly timed decision.

abstract: ATTRACTIONS    Museums and Sites    AMERICAN MUSEUM OF THE MOVING IMAGE, 36-01 35th Avenue, at 36th Street, Astoria, Queens. Screenings this weekend: tonight at 7:30, ''Anything Can Happen'' (2003), directed by Shashanka Ghosh, in Hindi with English subtitles; part of ''Cinema India! Showcase 2004: The Changing Face of Indian Cinema.'' tomorrow at 2 p.m., ''The Awful Truth'' (1937), by Leo McCarey; at 4 p.m., ''My Favorite Wife'' (1940), by Garson Kanin; Sunday at 2 p.m., ''Once Upon a Honeymoon'' (1942), by Mr. McCarey; at 4:15 p.m., ''An Affair to Remember'' (1957), by Mr. McCarey; part of the retrospective ''Cary Grant X 5,'' Through July 18, ''Interactions/Art and Technology,'' a display of nine digital media works blending art with science. Part of the exhibition ''Digital Avant-Garde: Celebrating 25 Years of Ars Electronica,'' with nine interactive works on view at Eyebeam, 540 West 21st Street, Chelsea; (212) 252-5193. Through Jan. 23, ''Tim Burton Drawings,'' an exhibition of more than 24 drawings, watercolors and sketches related to that director's films. Museum hours: Wednesdays and Thursdays, noon to 5 p.m.; Fridays, noon to 8 p.m.; Saturdays and Sundays, 11 a.m. to 6 p.m.; and by appointment. Film and video showings are free with admission unless otherwise noted. Museum admission: $10; 65+ and students, $7.50; ages 5 to 18, $5; free for members and children 4 and younger and for everyone on Fridays from 4 to 8 p.m.; Friday-night screenings are extra. Information: www.movingimage.us or (718) 784-0077.

snippet: Excerpts from and thumbnail sketches of books about Times Square (Special Issue: Times Square at 100) (M)
lead_paragraph: Damon Runyon wasn't the only writer enchanted by Times Square. Significant histories of the area, by James Traub and by Anthony Bianco (excerpts below), have been published in this centennial year, and many notable older books, still available, retell its story.

abstract: Arts Briefing column; owners of Mercury Lounge rock club on East Houston Street make exclusive deal to present large concerts at Webster Hall dance club in East Village (S)
snippet: Arts Briefing column; owners of Mercury Lounge rock club on East Houston Street make exclusive deal to present large concerts at Webster Hall dance club in East Village (S)
lead_paragraph: Six years ago this month, the Mercury Lounge, the connoisseurs' rock club on East Houston Street, opened the 575-capacity Bowery Ballroom on Delancey Street to present bigger concerts. Now the owners have made an exclusive deal with Webster Hall, the 1,400-capacity dance club on East 11th Street in the East Village once known as the Ritz, to present even larger concerts there. The shows will be advertised as ''The Bowery Presents,'' and a new sound system will be installed, said John Moore, who books the Bowery. Webster Hall will be available for bookings seven nights a week, he said, although its late-night dancing on Thursdays, Fridays and Saturdays means that any other concerts will have to end by 11:30 p.m., resulting in strange meetings of rock and dance fans on their way in and out, already a common occurrence there. The concerts are to begin in August or September.
